<span id="freeTextContainer9554518829475080770">Forever Red is set in two parts, the past then a time jump to the present for part two. And I really like this, it totally worked for me because I am not a fan of excessive flashbacks. So thank you author for this, you rock!<br/><br/>If I&apos;m honest, for a fair bit through this book I didn&apos;t like Lia much at all, but slowly began to warm to her. Stupid teenage bullshit caused all the pain and suffering that could have been avoided If. She. Had. Only. Asked!! But, she knew she effed up, owned that and tried </span>
  <span id="freeText9554518829475080770" style="display:none">Forever Red is set in two parts, the past then a time jump to the present for part two. And I really like this, it totally worked for me because I am not a fan of excessive flashbacks. So thank you author for this, you rock!<br /><br />If I'm honest, for a fair bit through this book I didn't like Lia much at all, but slowly began to warm to her. Stupid teenage bullshit caused all the pain and suffering that could have been avoided If. She. Had. Only. Asked!! But, she knew she effed up, owned that and tried to move on with her life.<br /><br />Nate/Neil never ever got over losing Lia, and although both of them caved in very quickly to their rekindled (uh more like never lost) I do wish Nate had made her work for his forgiveness. She really was a prize idiot and should have given an epic grovel. This is why only 4 stars. A grovel would have rounded this read up to 5 stars because I bloody loved it. </span>
