<div id="review_1256473880" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1256473880" />
    <a title="Carissa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32223347-carissa"><img alt="Carissa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1437154385p2/32223347.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1256473880?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carissa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carissa" href="/user/show/32223347-carissa">Carissa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/25333776-forever-red">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1256473880" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer37227493057872441"><div>
<br/><div>
<br/>Told in dual POV&apos;s, the story spans differing time frames. One as teenagers, where we learn all about both characters; then we have them as adults, where they hash it all out and get a second chance at their romance story. The prelude to their adulthood was portrayed in apt detail. With each scene pulling wonderful emotions from the reader. My preference leaned towards the teenage years, as opposed to their adulthood. So my feelings towards the genre were quelled at Contemporary Romance. It fe</div></div></span>
  <span id="freeText37227493057872441" style="display:none"><div>
<br><div>
<br>Told in dual POV's, the story spans differing time frames. One as teenagers, where we learn all about both characters; then we have them as adults, where they hash it all out and get a second chance at their romance story. The prelude to their adulthood was portrayed in apt detail. With each scene pulling wonderful emotions from the reader. My preference leaned towards the teenage years, as opposed to their adulthood. So my feelings towards the genre were quelled at Contemporary Romance. It felt more of a Young Adult Romance.  The YA part makes up 60% of the story.  I would have preferred interchanging between past and present while the story was unveiled. The impact would have been compounded by the differing dynamics. Just my thoughts.</div>
<br><br>Carina gives us teenagers from opposite sides of the track. A young girl, that doesn't fit into the social circles or the cliched high school teenage girl. A young  trailer park girl that uses boys and men, in a game with her "like" minded girlfriends, to gain points, over each other, in order to win. Cecelia's aim is to work as hard as possible to get out of her town. Then enter, Nathaniel Kelly, the new boy at school, the new target on so many girls radar. But he only has eyes for one girl. It started off as a game, they became friends and it ended in a love that conquered all. Nathaniel was and is such a sweet and gorgeous young man. So simple and absolutely devoted to Cecelia. I loved loved Neil, he was absolutely the most supportive boyfriend ever. Also he wasn't the stereotypical teenage boy. Their love story was so refreshing to read.</div><br><br><a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-TvWQgjaLNWk/VTFWs0pwkhI/AAAAAAAACMc/kAPiQJGKTN0/s1600/PicMonkey%2BCollage1.jpg" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1429366019i/14577047._SX540_.jpg" height="300" width="400" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br><br>When Nathaniel's plans changed to factor Cecelia into his future, his mother was furious. In his family's eyes, he was choosing a girl over them. His mother tried everything to change his mind and lure him onto a different girl. It didn't work; just infuriated him so much more. However, the attempts and the change in his future, wasn't lost upon Lia. She couldn't allow him to give up all he has ever wanted and worked towards for a trailer trash, man eating girl. Lia sacrificed her love to maintain the dreams of the love of her life and his future. A future she couldn't allow him to give up because of her. In doing so she maintained a lie that she cheated with his best friend while he was at home for the summer. This was the end of everything for Neil and Lia. <br><br>******<br><br><br>More than a decade later, Neil and Lia meet unexpectedly.<br><br><br>Neil is now a world famous Country music tatted bad boy, and Lia finds herself teaching a classroom full of boisterous teenagers. Lia has been following his career, and has bittersweet feelings whenever she reads about him.  While, Neil looked all over for her, hallucinating at times over spotting her ever so often. Feeling angry that she didn't choose to stay and fight for them and their future, but instead running away. He didn't believe she cheated, but because of the anger and shock he was frozen. She moved faster than he thought and by the time he came searching for her. She was long gone. Seeing her at his concert for the first time in years. All the anger came flooding back. But hell if he wasn't happy to see her. She was the same, yet so different.<br><br><a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-rrOeTRZkXCA/VTGAUT4JFjI/AAAAAAAACMw/LfJG4boP5Do/s1600/PicMonkey%2BCollage2.jpg" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1429366019i/14577048._SX540_.jpg" height="235" width="400" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br><br>Happy to reunite and yet so scared that the past will continue to haunt them. Lia wants only one night with Neil. A birthday gift, one that will keep her wanting more. Knowng the body of a boy is so much different from the body of a <b>MAN.</b><br>Things start to speed up at this point and we find Lia going on tour with Neil. I sipmly thought everything started to move to fast and Neil just too easily accepted Lia back into his life and was absolutely too forgiving. He started to become unrealistic to me. He was too everthing nice and sweet and not enough ansgt and anger. The scale was inbalanced. Forever Red was an enjoyable and ok read for me.<br><br><b>*ARC provided by Love Between the Sheets Promotion on behalf of the author for an honest reveiw* Thanks!</b><br></span>
  <a data-text-id="37227493057872441" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
