<div id="review_1241852314" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1241852314" />
    <a title="Lauren ♥ Inked in Chapters" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13897648-lauren-inked-in-chapters"><img alt="Lauren ♥ Inked in Chapters" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526638030p2/13897648.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1241852314?book_show_action=true">Mar 31, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren ♥ Inked in Chapters" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren ♥ Inked in Chapters" href="/user/show/13897648-lauren-inked-in-chapters">Lauren ♥ Inked in Chapters</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13897648-lauren-inked-in-chapters?shelf=favs">favs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13897648-lauren-inked-in-chapters?shelf=blog-tour-review-requested">blog-tour-review-requested</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1241852314" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6843735685181545985">You can read this and other reviews at <a href='http://www.inkedinchapters.net' rel='nofollow noopener'>Inked in Chapters</a><br/><br/><br/>I’m going to start this review off by telling you exactly what you need to know:<br/><br/><b>You need. To read. This book.</b><br/><br/>I haven’t come away from a book feeling like this in months. The funny thing? I wasn’t even sure I wanted to read it. When it finally showed up on my kindle and I looked at the length, I literally groaned out load. Then I wrote Sarah saying that it was 6K something lines and I would never finish it. I didn’t just finish it, I devoure</span>
  <span id="freeText6843735685181545985" style="display:none">You can read this and other reviews at <a href="http://www.inkedinchapters.net" rel="nofollow noopener">Inked in Chapters</a><br /><br /><br />I’m going to start this review off by telling you exactly what you need to know:<br /><br /><b>You need. To read. This book.</b><br /><br />I haven’t come away from a book feeling like this in months. The funny thing? I wasn’t even sure I wanted to read it. When it finally showed up on my kindle and I looked at the length, I literally groaned out load. Then I wrote Sarah saying that it was 6K something lines and I would never finish it. I didn’t just finish it, I devoured it.<br /><br /><i>
  <blockquote>I wanted to know the man Nathaniel Kelly had become because I missed the boy he was.</blockquote>
</i><br /><br />Forever Read is broken up into two parts – past and present. Usually this isn’t my thing. I like the story to flow in a certain direction and hate getting into the past only to be chucked straight into the present. Somehow Carina made it work for me. The story was anything but predictable. I had all these preconceived ideas of how Nate/Neil and Lia/CeCe’s story would unfold. Carina repeatedly knocked me down a peg or two. 20% into the story I had no idea what would happen next. It was a constant roller coaster ride of emotional excitement.<br /><br /><i>
  <blockquote>The one thing I never expected, the one thing I left out of my perfect plan, was that if someone wants to get across badly enough, they don’t even need a bridge. They’ll jump in head first and swim. And Nate Kelly? He was a goddamn strong swimmer.</blockquote>
</i><br /><br />This book is long – it spans what feels like a lifetime – and I don’t want to get into everything this second chance romance involves. We’d be here all day. What I do want to say is that <i>Forever Red</i> is similar and yet altogether different than books of this genre. It’s more. The characters are extremely well developed, the plot line is intense - with twists and turns, and the writing flows effortlessly. It’s easy to say that <i>Forever Red</i> has secured a spot as one of my top reads of 2015. It had even found a place on my top reads of all-time list. It’s <b>THAT</b> good. <br /><br />*Given an ARC in exchange for an honest review*</span>
  <a data-text-id="6843735685181545985" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
